The practice blends elements of [[:en:Hindu astrology|Indian astrology]] (a fusion of [[:en:Western astrology|Western astrology]] and ancient Indian lunar astrology), Taoist celestial deity worship, and {{ill|Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|ja|陰陽五行説|1=Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|13=User:Immanuelle/Yin-Yang and Wuxing Theory|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 陰陽五行思想}}. It determines auspicious and inauspicious days based on the movements of celestial bodies such as the [[:en:Big Dipper|Big Dipper]], [[:en:Navagraha|Navagraha]], {{ill|Zodiac|ja|十二宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zodiac|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to サイン (占星術)}}, and lunar mansions like the {{ill|Nakshatra|ja|二十七宿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakshatra|qq=}} or [[:en:Twenty-Eight Mansions|Lunar mansions]]. When an inauspicious day is identified, practitioners would perform rituals to honor the deities associated with those stars to improve fortune.
The foundational scriptures include the {{ill|Sutra of Sukuyokyo|ja|宿曜経|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sutra of Sukuyokyo|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 文殊師利菩薩及諸仙所説吉凶時日善悪宿曜経}}, {{ill|Brahma Agni Sutra|ja|梵天火羅九曜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Brahma Agni Sutra|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, and {{ill|Shichi Yō Seishin Betsu Gōhō|ja|七曜星辰別行法|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shichi Yō Seishin Betsu Gōhō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}. One unique technique is {{ill|Sankū Hikkyū|ja|三九秘宿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sankū Hikkyū|qq=}}, which has a simplified version popularized as "Shukuyō astrology."
In [[:en:Mikkyō|Esoteric Buddhism]], selecting auspicious dates for rituals such as statue construction, ceremonies, or consecration was a crucial task. The {{ill|Mahāvairocanābhisaṃbodhi Sūtra Commentary|ja|大日経疏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mahāvairocanābhisaṃbodhi Sūtra Commentary|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} by [[:en:Yi Xing|Ichigyō]] emphasized the importance of this process as a test of an [[:en:Acharya|Acharya]]'s abilities.
Monks such as [[:en:Kūkai|Kūkai]], [[:en:Ennin|Ennin]], and [[:en:Enchin|Enchin]] brought the {{ill|Sutra of Sukuyokyo|ja|宿曜経|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sutra of Sukuyokyo|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 文殊師利菩薩及諸仙所説吉凶時日善悪宿曜経}} to Japan, and {{ill|Ninkan|ja|仁観|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninkan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} further developed its study. In {{ill|957|ja|957|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/957|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 900}} ([[:en:Tiande|Tento era]] 1), {{ill|Nichien|ja|日延|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nichien|qq=}} brought the {{ill|Futen Calendar|ja|符天暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futen Calendar|qq=}} from [[:en:Wuyue|Wuyue]], intensifying research. {{ill|Hōzō (Japanese monk)|ja|法蔵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōzō (Japanese monk)|qq=}} in [[:en:Ōwa|Ōwa era]] 1 ({{ill|963|ja|963|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/963|qq=}}) debated [[:en:Kamo no Yasunori|Kamo no Yasunori]] over the use of auspicious dates for [[:en:Emperor Murakami|Emperor Murakami]]’s offerings. This marked the formal establishment of Shukuyōdō in Japan.
== Legacy ==
* In the [[:en:The Tale of Genji|Genji Monogatari]], a scene in the "Kiritsubo" chapter describes [[:en:Hikaru Genji|Hikaru Genji]]’s fate being predicted by a Shukuyō astrologer. * During the [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]], [[:en:Kujō Yoritsune|Fujiwara no Yoritsune]] employed a Shukuyō practitioner, {{ill|Chinhyo|ja|珍誉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinhyo|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, to select auspicious locations for the {{ill|Shogunate|ja|御所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shogunate|qq=}}.
