Monks such as [[:en:Kūkai|Kūkai]], [[:en:Ennin|Ennin]], and [[:en:Enchin|Enchin]] brought the {{ill|Sutra of Sukuyokyo|ja|宿曜経|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sutra of Sukuyokyo|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 文殊師利菩薩及諸仙所説吉凶時日善悪宿曜経}} to Japan, and {{ill|Ninkan|ja|仁観|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninkan|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} further developed its study. In [[:en:957|957]] ([[:en:Tiande|Tento era]] 1), {{ill|Nichien|ja|日延|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nichien|qq=}} brought the {{ill|Futen Calendar|ja|符天暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futen Calendar|qq=}} from [[:en:Wuyue|Wuyue]], intensifying research. {{ill|Hōzō (Japanese monk)|ja|法蔵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōzō (Japanese monk)|qq=}} in [[:en:Ōwa|Ōwa era]] 1 ([[:en:963|963]]) debated [[:en:Kamo no Yasunori|Kamo no Yasunori]] over the use of auspicious dates for [[:en:Emperor Murakami|Emperor Murakami]]’s offerings. This marked the formal establishment of Shukuyōdō in Japan.
== Legacy ==
* In the [[:en:The Tale of Genji|Genji Monogatari]], a scene in the "Kiritsubo" chapter describes [[:en:Hikaru Genji|Hikaru Genji]]’s fate being predicted by a Shukuyō astrologer. * During the [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]], [[:en:Kujō Yoritsune|Fujiwara no Yoritsune]] employed a Shukuyō practitioner, {{ill|Chinhyo|ja|珍誉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chinhyo|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, to select auspicious locations for the {{ill|Shogunate|ja|御所|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shogunate|qq=}}.
